MODE: Hold Scope

Risk Assessment
Player-side demand is unvalidated. This is the single biggest risk. The product is named, designed, and positioned around a user (the 13–18 player) who has not been heard from. The Q4 metric (60% weekly logging, unprompted) is an honest test, but the founder should expect a meaningfully higher-than-comfortable probability of missing it. If REQ-001 ships and players don't log, nothing else matters.
No named pilot club. The wedge (E) is structurally unsafe until a specific academy is committed. Building before securing the pilot is building blind.
Triangle complexity vs. pilot scale. Wedge (E) keeps full triangle scope (3 roles) at narrow audience (~15 players). That's a lot of surface area to build, polish, and debug for a 30-person pilot — and Q5 forbids cutting features mid-pilot. If feasibility slips, the ship date does, and there's no onboarding deadline (Open Risk #2) to force a reckoning.
No revenue line in the kill criteria. Q6 kills on engagement metrics but not on cost. If infrastructure + founder time burns through runway during the pilot, nothing in REQUIREMENTS.md tells you to stop.
Recommendation
Hold Scope is the right call. Build exactly the 5 requirements as specced, do not expand, do not add a sixth, and do not begin until a named pilot club is committed in writing. The pilot is an evidence-gathering exercise, not a product launch — treat every line of code as paid for in information return, not user delight. Before writing any code, close two gaps: (a) name the pilot club, (b) interview at least 3 target players (13–18) and capture their words on the development-tracking pain. If those interviews surface zero player-side enthusiasm, downgrade to a coach-first wedge before building anything.

